segments.text: If you're really able to understand the importance of planning to this kind of community, to this community, and how we as planners have handled it, I don't need to dwell on the transportation plan.
I think it's very obvious to everyone why we approved the transportation plan, and we used that as a way to carry forth our planning process, but we haven't always done that.

The planners under the direction of Kern Ewing and other persons who have succeeded Kern have made a very honest and diligent effort to press the city management and city council into allowing us to develop another comprehensive plan, something that will be acceptable and adoptable by the city government of Corpus Christi, meaning its city council.
Who were some of these other people?
with the demise of Kern Ewing and Linus Jameson and of the entire community renewal program itself.
What happened to Kern Ewing?
Kern had left.
He had worked himself into it.
He was a very highly principled planner.
He didn't compromise his principles very much, regardless of the pressures that were put on him.
And I think Kern, like a lot of idealistic persons that are highly principled, also didn't realize the difficulty that our administration was in in pursuing a comprehensive plan.
Let me just say, I think it was just by mutual agreement it would be better.
It was both best for the city of Corpus Christi and best for Kern that he resign.
And he did.
And everyone who has resigned from our office has generally gone to a better job.
Kern had gone to, he became the director of planning for Bob Armstrong in the state land office after he left Corpus.
And so it was great.
Linus Jameson then assumed the title under the reorganization.
as a senior planner.
And then who were some of the other staff planners who were leading the city council to ask very serious questions about community improvement?
Well, I think the only one seriously who took a very active role in doing that, at least through the planning commission, was Mr. Bruce McClendon.
Bruce McClendon was a senior planner.
hired by Mr. Winger, or Mr. Anderson, and worked in the planning department.
An extremely capable person.
Bruce was not within our community renewal function.
Very quick, let me tell you what happened, and I feel I can get my date straight.
I think it was around late 1974, early 75.
city manager decided that he wanted to reorganize, Mark Towns, reorganize the city government.

And at that time, they decided to create one of the super departments, or four super departments, for the purpose of reducing the number of people who actually, who had to deal with the city manager directly.
Although, you know, before he had to have to work with everyone on a one-to-one basis.
And Mr.
Towns' type of management at that time was,

to do everything, to supervise everything, to personally sign off on everything, even from hiring people at lower grades, lower grade people, to personally signing off on all subdivision things and all zoning actions and recommendations.
And for that reason, Mr. Townsend worked from 8 o'clock in the morning to midnight every night.
And he usually worked seven days a week.

Under the reorganization, the Community Renewal Program phased out and we phased in, of course the money was phasing out too, we phased in the 701 Planning Program, which Linus Jameson came in charge of.
That became the long-range planning division of the Department of Planning.
And also in that reorganization, it made Mr. Jonas Briones the Director of Planning and Urban Development.
Mr. Anderson, who was already at retirement age, if he had chose to stay on, would have been the Director of Intergovernmental Affairs.
And that job simply would have been coordinating about city activities with other governmental jurisdictions.
Mr. Anderson decided at that time that he would rather retire.
And he went from there.
He moved into, which I'm sure you're aware of now,
consulting work, not on a full-time basis, but part-time, and he was associated with Harlem Bartholomew in the consulting office he set up down here.
Under the leadership of Mr. Briones, who is, I don't really consider Mr. Briones anti-planning.
I hear a lot of people say that he is, but he's not.
But one of the things that Mr. Briones wanted to emphasize since Kern left, Kern never joined us over here,
He resigned before the changeover took place.
We physically moved our offices from the center of downtown over to the present city hall.
And we had long-range planning and we had current planning.
And I was in the long-range planning still just as a planner.
And one of the things that had happened in that transition, too, is that
In 1974, the city just had rejected by the Department of Transportation, Urban Mass Transportation Administration, an application for purchase of new buses.
It was a Section 3 capital grant.

And the reason it was rejected is because the Department of Transportation had extended its planning requirements to cover transit operations and required that prior to awarding any capital grants for purchase of major capital items, such as buses or building new facilities,
that they would want to see some sort of overall planning document.
In other words, some sort of assurance that this isn't a fly-by-night type of thing.
These decisions are made within the parameters of a well-thought-out growth document for transit improvement.
Same kinds of requirements that are placed on highway improvements.
I was asked to temporarily take over the assignment of doing a five-year transit development plan, a long range transit plan for the city.
What year was this?
This was 1974 that I took that over.
That was when John Hurtin was heading up UMTA in Washington, I believe.
He may have been, yeah.
I really didn't at that time pay too much attention
paid too much mind to who was heading up what.
I dealt primarily with the regional offices.
And I got into it.
I really enjoyed it.
I loved the transit work that I did.
I liked getting around all those buses.
But all the time, I thought this was only a temporary assignment, and that eventually, a transportation planner
as opposed to a General Staff Planner would be brought in to assume those duties, and I would go back to my own duties as a physical planner for the Advanced Planning or Long Range Planning Division.
And it didn't happen.
We ended up, Ernest created a Transportation Planning Division within the department and promoted me from Planner 1 to Planner 2 to a Senior Planner, and there I stayed.

And I got involved in very few other planning activities, but it did allow me the opportunity, as someone not involved, to observe as an outsider close to everything what was happening, since my transportation plans, or the city's transportation plans, was the only tool that we could push planning programs through.
Linus Jamison was still part of the old Community of No Program, and therefore there was still a lot of resentment, I think, from the top down, of her ideas on planning.
Let me tell you, first of all, that if we can put this planning in perspective, Mr. Townsend's idea of a plan was the zoning ordinance.
In his opinion, and he had said many times, we don't need a comprehensive plan, we have one, and that's the zoning ordinance.
The present zoning.
you can fully realize how that makes us planners feel, knowing that that's very noteworthy.
That's a little surprising considering the fact that he had undertaken a substantial number of planning courses at Cornell.
I think I can understand
Mr. Townsend's point of view to a certain extent.
One of the things that I believe bothered him about planning more than anything else was that plans, in a sense, suggested a commitment to do something further down the road.
than what the city manager was willing to do, you know, to change various land uses, to affect certain growth trends, to...
There was a difference in time frames.
And he didn't like these commitments, even though they were just insinuated.

And he was very afraid of the fact, for example, if someone would bring in a general land use plan and they'd look at it and say, see, it's got some red there, and that meant you promised back whenever you approved that plan
You promised that I was going to be able to develop that property as commercial, and that wasn't the intent of a plan.
And as you know and I know, a plan isn't worth the paper it's written on unless it's flexible enough to meet the needs of the community.
And Mr. Townsend did not want to have to deal with that kind of flexibility.
Mr. Townsend's idea of a planning function...
He sounds like he didn't want to deal with commitment either, let alone flexibility.
Mr. Townsend's forte...

finances as most effective managers are understanding the finances of the city that they run and it is a big business and his understanding of finances didn't fit any kind of any kind of plan and his idea of planning or his idea of what a planning department should do
was to provide management with information on a day-to-day basis that they need for making a decision.

And if those planning kinds of documents that we develop address what some of our conditions would be 10, 15, 20 years down the road, it didn't mean much to him because he wasn't concerned about that.
He was concerned about capital improvements over a three-year period.
and next year.
New York City went bankrupt with such a short range perspective.

I suppose you could say that because Corpus Christi has been such conservative in its administration and also very conservative in its growth that in a way we were inadvertently blessed in that we have developed
for appearances sake, as a well-planned community.

But what's really happened is that we have been subjected to the growth spurts that San Antonio's and Austin's and Houston's and Dallas's have been, because if we had, I think everything would have been well out of control.
And also that you've got to understand the community itself,
people who've lived here, who are the leaders here, are very proud of this city.
They're very proud of the way it looks.
They're very proud of the fact that it's considered an extremely clean city.
And, you know, I've heard people from the outside, very professional people, like from New York, to say that it's so clean it's sterile.
And that's not good.
Well, I'm not sure whether that's good or bad.
I'm not even sure if I know what they mean by sterile.
I just know that
We do have a lot more room for growth.
But yes, you're right about that's what drove New York City into bankruptcy.
But we're not New York City.
We're very small.
We're a population of around, we're a population in 1970 of 201,000, and we're a population in 1980 of 230,000.
And the majority of that growth has occurred over the last four years.
Largely, what do you attribute the growth to?
Well, I think the kind of growth that we have, our growth is attributed primarily to natural increases.
We haven't been subjected to a heavy in-migration of new people.
I believe we're going to be seeing that.
I think that the job opportunities in Corpus Christi are not that good.
The job opportunities that are here
are in the petroleum industry, usually for skilled type of laborers.
And the petroleum industry pretty well takes care of that.
And the other kinds of jobs that are here, and on a much lesser scale, are in the domestic area.
People working in hotels and restaurants and cleaners, et cetera.
Tourists.
Yeah, people that are responding to the tourist needs.
Tourists is one of the major, if not the major, industry approaches here.
Our growth over the past has been natural increases as opposed to a migration trend.

As a matter of fact, the Community Renewal Program did a study in 1974, which was what we entitled a Household Movement Study, in which we documented that we were losing people, people moving out, moving out primarily to Houston and then to San Antonio.
The only thing that kept our population even, or with a very minimal growth, was our natural increase.
That was a very controversial report.
I bet it was.
Because it was telling the community leaders, the Chamber of Commerce people, that people were leaving.
They couldn't, because the kinds of people that were attracting, everyone wants to attract these skilled laborers, the high-income people.
That's not it.
This community doesn't have that to offer.
And maybe it will.
It is of sorts a very...
favorite in the retirement area.
It is also a retirement community for a lot of the elderly affluent people.
Not people who live in noble homes.
No, not people who live in noble homes.
I think a lot of people who buy condominiums and townhouses of sorts or apartments.
The Navy, for example, the Naval Air Station Facility, which also includes an Army helicopter repair depot,
both of which employ a lot of civilians and a lot of Navy personnel.
These people are brought in usually from the outside.
They're highly skilled people, and they enjoy it here.
And when they retire from those jobs, they stay here.
And that's where a lot of the retirement people come from.
Or people who have served here in the Navy or Army at one time before in the past, and then they retire, come back here because they like to.
Did I lose my train of thought here?
All right, picking up with Mr. McClendon.
Mr. McClendon was senior planner, hired a senior planner from Oklahoma.
I believe he had been a director of planning for one of the small cities in Oklahoma.
I don't recall which one it was.
Maybe it was Lawton.
I'm not sure.
Graduate of the OU planning program.

very sound planner very good person and if you ever if anyone knows bruce you know that he is a what i consider a mover he was in charge of planning and there was a little bit of conflict when we made the transition here we have a long-range planning division under the direction of a senior planner doing long-range planning work that bruce extremely capable of doing and was working with her miss jameson
being a part of the Old Community Road Program and also looking for a change and wanting to get, you know, move forward.
And as you said in the past, Bob, people, planners, young, particularly young planners, their advancement usually comes with several jobs, not just staying with one city.
And Linna did.
She left in 75, I believe, or 76, can't remember exactly, and went up to Kansas City to work for
the planning office up there, and I understand she's done very well.

At the time, prior to, I think one of the things that helped Ms. Jameson leave was the fact that during her stay here, although she wasn't demoted in any way, Bruce was put in charge of her program as a senior planner, and she became answerable to Bruce.
And professionally, I think she felt a little bit hurt with regard to that.
But Bruce was going to also was very impressive in that he was going to
provide a new direction in planning, and I think the management people, the administrators, the city manager, Mr. Briones, all felt that he had what it took to get the job done.
And Bruce did.
I've never seen an office produce, a planning office produce so many reports in such a short period of time.
Under Bruce's leadership, prepared and published an updated economic study of the city of Corpus Christi, physical determinants of land use study for the city, and
A very well-known document among other professional planners is what we call our housing element, but actually not known at all.
And the economic study, the housing element, they all had policy-type statements in it.
And all these documents were a forerunner of Bruce's ultimate plan of getting
Planning Commission and City Council to agree to allow the staff to prepare for the city a comprehensive plan.
Now here we're coming back again.
Mr. Ewing's downfall, Mrs. Jameson's downfall, was trying to be, was pressuring the preparation and approval of a comprehensive plan.
Now, and all of which have been unsuccessful.
And there's ways of moving projects through an elected body and there's ways of not doing it.
I feel that I have the political savvy of how to handle delicate documents like that and not move them through so quickly and help convince things that I have picked up from Mr. Cunningham.
And Bruce thought that he could probably do it too.
You know, he was a gifted person as far as persuading people to do things.
And up until Bruce came in and started doing this,
The only thing that, as far as planning documents that we had utilized, which were approved, were the updates to the transportation plans called annual reports.
And we did that every year.
And again, it was a requirement.
But it was an effective requirement, and it kept us on target with our long-range transportation plan codes.
But that wasn't enough.
And I think the annual reports began to deteriorate as time went on.
And they really never did deal with enough detail with other elements of a comprehensive plan.
And that's what Bruce was trying to do.
He was trying to bring to the city an approved document that dealt with housing, that dealt with community facilities, that dealt with land uses, that dealt with urban design.
very important.
You mentioned the housing report.
What is the status of that and what is the cause of the status?
You're probably a little bit more familiar with the housing report in that you had a lot to do in getting it started under a program of a local section.
It was an AIP section at that time.
Bruce brought in, and of course Bruce was a real
real big on continuing education of our fellow planners in this area, and you were brought down as an invited guest or however, but you agreed to come down and you taught basically a course here.
I didn't get to take it, but you taught a course here, and the project was to do a plan summary, which the students or the staff, the staff members were
That was your participants in the course.
The kind of classic unified summary for a comprehensive plan.
That's right.
As the final examination of the course.
And one of the results of this course was a unified summary that was tied to a housing element.
And the housing element is a large report.
It's extremely well done.
It looks good.
It was professionally prepared and published.
And there was a lot of arm twisting to get it published.

But it contained within that housing element a lot of goals, housing policies that actually, after it was done and printed and Mr. Townsend looked at it, felt that, well, I do not want, he did not personally want to be held committed to those kinds of goals and selling those goals to city councils as they would change from year to year.
And...
I believe there's about 150, 200 copies of that report that were published.
And Mr. McClendon tried in vain on many occasions to get a formal and official release of that report, which never came.
And what eventually happened is that for better or worse, the report was boxed up and put back in storage.
It has always been the intention
or at least Mr. McLendon was told, that we want to eventually release the report.
We want to handle it in our own time frame and as delicately as possible.
I don't believe it was ever the intention to pigeonhole the report so no one could see it.
It wasn't that damage to the report, but it was very aggressive.
And it did set some long-range goals and commendable goals, but it's also some very, very strong objectives.
With your new city manager now, is there any effort being made to conduct a review of that at the planning commission level?

Well, you have to understand that the new city manager has only been here several months, and at this moment, although he seems to be an extremely sharp individual, which he is, the reason he was hired, you could well understand that
what he's doing now is letting things run as they had been under the leadership of people that were in charge prior to Mr. Townsend.

And we did go through another major reorganization under Townsend prior to his departure, where before we had city manager Marvin Townsend, assistant city manager, and then four major department heads in charge of what I call super departments.
The new reorganization effective down last year, we created that we had city manager, deputy city manager, which Mr. Briones was elevated to deputy city manager, and four assistant city managers.
And these assistant city managers, this organizational structure was in place, although very new, at the time Mr. Martin, our new city manager, came on board.
And understandably, as I said earlier, he's just going to
sort of watch over things, monitor it.
He's made some critical decisions.
We have no feedback yet on what his feelings are about planning.
But I think after he's been there for maybe six months to maybe a year, that he will start bringing his own personal style of management
And I believe we'll see very shortly what his thoughts are on planning.
And of course, we keep our fingers crossed as to hoping that he would allow us to move forward in this direction.
At this time, Mr. Martin probably does not know or is not aware that there is a housing element tucked away back in the back somewhere.
And he may or may not be impressed with it.
I don't know.
It's hard to say.
But in the meantime, this department
seeing as what happened to other planters.
It's very important to understand that what Bruce and what Linus and what the Kern Ewings all tried to do was extremely commendable.
It was done very well.
And it was done, for the most part, a losing cause.
And the only people who lose, really, is the city and the planning department, our own goals.
Mr. McLendon had since left and went
become director of planning at Galveston, and now he's currently the director of planning of the city of Beaumont.
And Linda Jamison left, and she got a much higher paying position with the city of Kansas, Kansas City, and she's doing extremely well.
But the real losers is the city, and I think we as planners are trying to do more of
Well, we're going to try another approach.
You've got to keep trying.
And this time it's a little bit more low-key.
We're not pressing long-range planning.
We are implying it.
We're bringing it in slowly.
This department and our staff have become very responsive to short-range needs.
We have taken our emphasis on long-range planning and applied it to the neighborhoods.
We do not use a 2,000-year plan.
or a 2002-year plan, a 20-year plan.
We don't go by that anymore.
We have an ultimate plan.
And we have five-year improvements, priorities.
And so in one sense, what is the ultimate plan?
An ultimate plan is what our concept of what the city is going to look like when it's ultimately developed.
Where is this plan housed?
This plan happens to be
compromise to the unified summary prepared by your class.
It was our way of saving it.
And what we have done, we have calculated out all the different types of land uses and impacts it would have on the city's growth if they should be developed.
We've incorporated into it densities, housing densities that we need, commercial properties, etc.
And we've also go back into using, we've done this under the auspices of the transportation plan again because
One of the things we're required to do in order to continue highway improvements is to maintain the 20-year plan.
So we have to do our traffic assignments for the year 2000.
Where is this ultimate plan?
Well, the ultimate plan is about 50% through, and we've done it by planning area.

as El Paso did, and Kern, you know, since Kern came from El Paso and I came from El Paso, we set up the city in basically five planning areas, and we worked primarily in the two planning areas that were most critical, most of, you know, the ones that were subjected to the most growth, and that's the northwest planning area and the southeast planning area.
We have at this point nothing published, but we do have all of our documentations and materials.
That's not in there.
No, this here is our
transportation study area with our traffic zones.
And these are our sectors.
And although this really does not relate to our planning area.
Well, the name Ultimate Plan fascinates me because it is unique in the animals and plants to have a document called Ultimate.
That I find interesting.
We may find it more interesting than you think after we get caught up with the language.
It's a word selection game, really.
Ultimate seems to be more acceptable to other people than, let's say, a plan that says 1980 or 1990 plan.
A lot of people are still afraid, as far as from the administrator's point of view, that a plan implies a commitment to do certain things.
That's why in my classes now, I encourage the students to think in terms of horizons that are not time horizons, but population horizons.
Well, exactly.
And if you have X people, then you have this sort of thing happening.
We reject in the Corpus Christi area.
Well, we do have some rejections that carry us through 20 years.
346,000 by the year 2000.
we use that kind of population target to identify the kinds of services will be needed to address those population needs.
But the timing is very flexible, and it's of very little consequence.
One of the things we accomplished, and I think this is interesting, and I don't know if we have compromised our own
